{
  "What is the formula for percent yield?": "",
  "(Theoretical yield / Actual yield) x 100%": "",
  "(Actual yield / Theoretical yield) x 100%": "",
  "(Actual yield - Theoretical yield) x 100%": "",
  "(Theoretical yield - Actual yield) / Actual yield x 100%": "",
  "Percent yield = (actual yield / theoretical yield) x 100%. It compares what was actually obtained to the maximum possible amount.": "",
  "If the theoretical yield of a reaction is 50 g and the actual yield is 40 g, what is the percent yield?": "",
  "125%": "",
  "90%": "",
  "40%": "",
  "80%": "",
  "Percent yield = (40/50) x 100% = 80%. This means 80% of the maximum possible product was obtained.": "",
  "Can the percent yield of a reaction ever exceed 100%?": "",
  "Yes, if a catalyst is used": "",
  "Not in theory, but measured values may exceed 100% due to impurities or measurement error": "",
  "No, it always equals exactly 100%": "",
  "Yes, if the reaction is highly exothermic": "",
  "Theoretically, percent yield cannot exceed 100%, but experimental errors, impurities, or incomplete drying of product can cause the measured actual yield to appear greater than the theoretical yield.": "",
  "Which of the following is NOT a common reason for a percent yield below 100%?": "",
  "Incomplete reaction": "",
  "Side reactions forming unwanted products": "",
  "Using a balanced equation": "",
  "Loss of product during transfer or purification": "",
  "Using a balanced equation is necessary for calculating theoretical yield and does not cause a low percent yield. Side reactions, losses, and incomplete reactions all reduce actual yield.": "",
  "If a reaction has a percent yield of 100%, what does this indicate?": "",
  "The reaction was endothermic": "",
  "The reaction reached equilibrium": "",
  "A catalyst was used": "",
  "All reactants were consumed and the maximum product was obtained": "",
  "A 100% yield means the actual yield equals the theoretical yield -- every bit of limiting reagent was converted to product with no losses.": "",
  "A student obtains 15 g of product from a reaction with a theoretical yield of 25 g. What is the percent yield?": "",
  "75%": "",
  "60%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "Percent yield = (15/25) x 100% = 60%. The student obtained 60% of the theoretical maximum.": "",
  "What is the actual yield if the theoretical yield is 80 g and the percent yield is 75%?": "",
  "100 g": "",
  "60 g": "",
  "80 g": "",
  "20 g": "",
  "Actual yield = (percent yield / 100) x theoretical yield = (75/100) x 80 = 60 g.": "",
  "Which factor most directly increases the percent yield of a reaction?": "",
  "Improving the technique to reduce product loss": "",
  "Writing a more balanced equation": "",
  "Using a larger beaker": "",
  "Increasing the amount of excess reagent": "",
  "Reducing product loss during filtration, transfer, and purification directly increases the actual yield and therefore the percent yield.": "",
  "How does the theoretical yield relate to the limiting reagent?": "",
  "Theoretical yield does not depend on any reagent": "",
  "Theoretical yield is based on the limiting reagent being completely converted to product": "",
  "Theoretical yield equals the mass of the limiting reagent": "",
  "Theoretical yield is calculated from the excess reagent": "",
  "The theoretical yield is calculated by assuming complete conversion of the limiting reagent to product, using the stoichiometric mole ratios from the balanced equation.": "",
  "A reaction has a theoretical yield of 100 g. If side reactions consume 10% of the reactant and 5 g of product is lost during filtration, what is the approximate actual yield?": "",
  "85 g": "",
  "95 g": "",
  "90 g": "",
  "If 10% is lost to side reactions, 90 g is produced. Losing 5 g in filtration leaves 85 g actual yield (85% percent yield).": "",
  "What does 'percent yield' mean?": "",
  "The percentage of solvent that evaporates": "",
  "The percentage of reactant that is consumed": "",
  "The percentage of energy released by the reaction": "",
  "The ratio of actual yield to theoretical yield, expressed as a percentage": "",
  "Percent yield is a measure of the efficiency of a reaction, calculated as (actual yield / theoretical yield) x 100%, comparing what was obtained to the maximum possible.": "",
  "What does 'actual yield' mean?": "",
  "The calculated maximum amount of product possible": "",
  "The mass of the limiting reagent": "",
  "The amount of product actually obtained from performing the reaction": "",
  "The amount predicted by Hess's law": "",
  "Actual yield is the amount of product that is physically obtained when a chemical reaction is carried out in the laboratory, which is typically less than the theoretical yield.": "",
  "What does 'theoretical yield' mean?": "",
  "The maximum amount of product calculated from stoichiometry assuming complete reaction": "",
  "The yield predicted by kinetics": "",
  "The average yield of all experiments": "",
  "The yield obtained after multiple trial runs": "",
  "Theoretical yield is the maximum amount of product that could be obtained if the limiting reagent is completely converted to product, as calculated from the balanced equation.": "",
  "What does 'side reaction' mean in the context of percent yield?": "",
  "An unwanted reaction that consumes reactants to form different products": "",
  "The reverse of the main reaction": "",
  "A reaction that increases the yield": "",
  "A reaction occurring at the same rate as the main reaction": "",
  "A side reaction is an unwanted competing reaction that consumes some of the reactants to form products other than the desired one, thereby reducing the percent yield.": "",
  "What does 'reaction efficiency' mean?": "",
  "How effectively reactants are converted into the desired product": "",
  "The number of steps in a reaction mechanism": "",
  "How quickly a reaction reaches completion": "",
  "The temperature at which a reaction occurs": "",
  "Reaction efficiency refers to how effectively a chemical reaction converts starting materials into the desired product, often measured by percent yield or atom economy.": "",
  "What does 'atom economy' mean?": "",
  "The percentage of atoms in the reactants that end up in the desired product": "",
  "The cost of atoms in a reaction": "",
  "The efficiency of balancing an equation": "",
  "The number of atoms balanced in an equation": "",
  "Atom economy measures the fraction of atoms from all reactants that appear in the desired product, and is an important concept in green chemistry for evaluating reaction efficiency.": "",
  "What does 'purification' mean in the context of isolating a product?": "",
  "The process of removing impurities and byproducts from the desired product": "",
  "Adding more reactant to increase yield": "",
  "Balancing the equation to ensure correct ratios": "",
  "Heating a reaction to completion": "",
  "Purification is the process of separating the desired product from impurities, unreacted materials, and byproducts, which can often reduce the actual yield.": "",
  "What does 'byproduct' mean in a chemical reaction?": "",
  "The limiting reagent of the reaction": "",
  "The main product of the reaction": "",
  "A catalyst used in the reaction": "",
  "A secondary and often unwanted product formed alongside the desired product": "",
  "A byproduct is a secondary substance produced during a chemical reaction in addition to the desired product, and its formation reduces the yield of the target product.": "",
  "What does 'quantitative reaction' mean?": "",
  "A reaction that goes to completion with essentially 100% yield": "",
  "A reaction used in quantitative analysis only": "",
  "A reaction involving only measurable quantities": "",
  "A reaction that produces a measurable amount of heat": "",
  "A quantitative reaction is one that proceeds to completion (or very nearly so), with virtually all of the limiting reagent converted to product, giving a percent yield at or near 100%.": "",
  "What does 'incomplete reaction' mean?": "",
  "A reaction with no products": "",
  "A reaction that does not proceed to full conversion of reactants to products": "",
  "A reaction that requires no energy input": "",
  "A reaction where the equation is not balanced": "",
  "An incomplete reaction is one in which not all of the limiting reagent is converted to product, resulting in an actual yield that is less than the theoretical yield.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company synthesizes 450 g of aspirin from a batch of salicylic acid. The theoretical yield was 520 g. The quality control team needs to determine the percent yield. What is it?": "",
  "92.0%": "",
  "78.3%": "",
  "115.6%": "",
  "86.5%": "",
  "Percent yield = (450/520) x 100% = 86.5%. The company achieved 86.5% efficiency in their aspirin synthesis.": "",
  "A student heats 10.0 g of KClO3 (MW = 122.6) to decompose it: 2KClO3 -> 2KCl + 3O2. The student collects 3.5 g of O2 (MW = 32). What is the percent yield?": "",
  "75.0%": "",
  "89.4%": "",
  "65.2%": "",
  "100%": "",
  "Moles KClO3 = 10.0/122.6 = 0.0816 mol. Moles O2 = 0.0816 x (3/2) = 0.1224 mol. Theoretical yield = 0.1224 x 32 = 3.917 g. Percent yield = (3.5/3.917) x 100% = 89.4%.": "",
  "A factory produces ammonia with a typical percent yield of 15% per pass (due to equilibrium limitations). If the theoretical yield for one pass is 200 kg of NH3, how much ammonia is actually produced per pass?": "",
  "15 kg": "",
  "200 kg": "",
  "30 kg": "",
  "170 kg": "",
  "Actual yield = (15/100) x 200 = 30 kg. The Haber process has a low single-pass yield due to equilibrium, so unreacted gases are recycled.": "",
  "A chemistry student wants to produce copper metal by reacting CuSO4 with zinc: CuSO4 + Zn -> ZnSO4 + Cu. Starting with 25.0 g of CuSO4 (MW = 159.6), the student obtains 8.5 g of Cu (MW = 63.5). What is the percent yield?": "",
  "68.0%": "",
  "54.0%": "",
  "85.5%": "",
  "92.3%": "",
  "Moles CuSO4 = 25.0/159.6 = 0.1566 mol. The 1:1 ratio gives 0.1566 mol Cu. Theoretical yield = 0.1566 x 63.5 = 9.94 g. Percent yield = (8.5/9.94) x 100% = 85.5%.": "",
  "A soap manufacturer reacts fat with NaOH to produce glycerol and soap. If the reaction has a percent yield of 92% and the theoretical yield of soap is 500 g, how much soap is actually produced?": "",
  "400 g": "",
  "500 g": "",
  "460 g": "",
  "543 g": "",
  "Actual yield = (92/100) x 500 = 460 g. With a 92% percent yield, the manufacturer obtains 460 g of soap from a theoretical maximum of 500 g.": "",
  "A researcher runs three trials of the same synthesis and obtains yields of 78%, 82%, and 85%. In the fourth trial, the researcher uses a more efficient purification method and obtains 91%. What most likely explains the improvement?": "",
  "The balanced equation changed": "",
  "The molar masses of the substances changed": "",
  "Less product was lost during the purification step": "",
  "The theoretical yield increased": "",
  "A more efficient purification technique reduces product loss, increasing the actual yield without changing the theoretical yield, thereby improving the percent yield.": "",
  "A student performs the reaction: Mg + 2HCl -> MgCl2 + H2. Using 2.43 g of Mg (MW = 24.3), the student collects 0.18 g of H2 (MW = 2). What is the percent yield?": "",
  "95%": "",
  "Moles Mg = 2.43/24.3 = 0.10 mol. The 1:1 ratio gives 0.10 mol H2. Theoretical yield = 0.10 x 2 = 0.20 g. Percent yield = (0.18/0.20) x 100% = 90%.": "",
  "An industrial process has a percent yield of 60% for step 1 and 80% for step 2. If the theoretical yield of the final product is 100 g (assuming both steps were 100%), what is the approximate overall actual yield?": "",
  "48 g": "",
  "140 g": "",
  "70 g": "",
  "For multi-step syntheses, overall yield is the product of individual yields: 0.60 x 0.80 = 0.48, so 48% of 100 g = 48 g. This shows why multi-step reactions often have low overall yields.": "",
  "A student reports a percent yield of 110%. The teacher suspects an error. Which of the following could explain this result?": "",
  "The student used excess reagent": "",
  "The product was not fully dried and contained residual water": "",
  "The student used a catalyst": "",
  "A yield over 100% is not physically possible. The most likely explanation is that the product was not fully dried, so residual water or solvent added mass, making the actual yield appear artificially high.": "",
  "A green chemistry lab compares two synthesis routes for the same product. Route A has a percent yield of 95% but produces toxic byproducts. Route B has a yield of 85% but produces no toxic waste. Which route is preferred from a green chemistry perspective and why?": "",
  "Neither; both routes are equally green": "",
  "Route A, because higher yield always means better chemistry": "",
  "Route B, because percent yield is the only factor that matters": "",
  "Route B, because green chemistry prioritizes minimizing hazardous waste alongside good yield": "",
  "Green chemistry considers environmental impact, waste reduction, and safety alongside yield. Route B's slightly lower yield is offset by producing no toxic byproducts, making it the greener choice.": ""
